crops.institution_involved: Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: An attractive leguminous shade tree which becomes 50 feet high, with a spreading habit and large pinnate leaves. The large racemes of pale-pink flowers appear before the leaves and somewhat resemble those of the black locust. For previous introduction see 99336.

crops.institution_involved: Arnold Arboretum
crops.description: A tall handsome tree, native to northern Japan, up to 75 feet high, with smooth, dark-brown bark and ovate or ovate-lanceolate sharply serrate leaves from 1 to 5 inches long. The single pink flowers, up to 11% inches wide, are in few-flowered clusters, and the black fruits are about the size of peas. For previous introduction see 93847.
A perennial grass which is used for grazing and for hay in Italy. For previous introduction see 89820.

crops.institution_involved: American Mission, Gaziantep
crops.description: A bulbous iris of the Xiphium section, native to Asia Minor, with one or two leaves that appear with or after the flowers. The flowers, over 4 inches across, are vivid blue except for the triangular white patch on the upper part of the falls.

crops.institution_involved: American Mission, Gaziantep
crops.description: An Oncocyclus iris, with narrowly sword-shaped leaves 6 to 9 inches long and one or two flowers veined and dotted with brown black on a brownish-white ground. Native to Asia Minor and Iran.

crops.institution_involved: American Mission, Gaziantep
crops.description: A short-stemmed iris of the section Juno, native to the mountainous regions of Asia Minor. The four to five linear-complicate leaves are barely 2 to 3 inches long at flowering time, becoming a foot long ultimately. The flowers are pale lilac with a dark-purple blotch at the top of the falls, an orange keel, and purple lines and spots.

crops.institution_involved: American Mission, Gaziantep
crops.description: An Oncocyclus iris with a fleshy, creeping rhizome and about six erect narrow leaves 9 inches or more high. The stem, 6 inches high, bears a single flower with falls and standards greenish yellow marked with brownish-red veins. Native to Asia Minor.

crops.institution_involved: American consul, Rangoon
crops.description: Received as Cycas siamensis, but the seeds appear to be of some leguminous plant allied to Dalbergia.
